hehe <p><img src="http://web.cci.clarku.edu/ebarry/ban.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umosushi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mosushi</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/15/02 8:07:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1718.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Did you get a warning/suspension yourself?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> if you attack them you get a warning and then suspension<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I hear this a lot from people, but so far, I've never heard it from someone that actually got warned or suspended.  I think it's an urban myth.  I spent a couple hours gathering parse data on Stormhammer.  No warnings at all and GMs are as common as white on rice there.<br>
<br>
If a GM says stop, of course I would, but I really don't believe they will or even that they have.  I think this is just a rumor from the &quot;game gestapo&quot; folks -- peeps that want to police everyone else's actions in game.  Unfortunately, this sometimes includes guides.  If a guide tells you to do something, you can always request a GM.  You really don't have to listen to anything guides tell you; they're just go-fers for the GM's.<br>
<br>
There's nothing gained from attacking him other than data to parse.  It's not as if you're gaining skill or xp or something from attacking.  It would be amusing to be accused of skill-farming when all my skills have been max'd for over a year.  However, many don't understand what you are doing, so they think you must be cheating.  Gah, what puny suspicious lil' minds.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Mosushi, Lizard Master of the Fish<br>
<i>"Mmmmm, fissssh!  You musst fillet thiss carefully!"</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucpete2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>c pete2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/15/02 8:11:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1718.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Did you get a warning/suspension yourself?</span><hr size=1> Well, it does smack of &quot;exploit,&quot;  so I wouldn't doubt it's happened.  Anyway, I had it happen again today against some kobold watchers who conned green in Toxx.  I thought about taking a screen shot, then I rrealized I didn't have away to host the pic so you could see it.  anyway. <p><br><br>-----BEGIN MAGIC CODE BLOCK-----<br>Version: 1.5<br>MYO/CM XCOM X+(-) PXX/EG P+ W N++ Ds/r A* a+ C++ G QH++ 666++>+++++ Y++<br>------END MAGIC CODE BLOCK------</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ulexxiclockwork.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lexxi Clockwork</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/16/02 9:38:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1718.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Skills ups</span><hr size=1> Had one of my guilds warriors who had just leveled up, test out the theories on skill-ups. Here are our findings.<br>
<br>
Green mobs - rare skill ups<br>
light blue mobs - very fast steady skills ups<br>
blue mobs - very steady skill ups<br>
even mobs - quirky skills ups, fast then slow; dependent on mobs ac?<br>
yellow mobs - quirky and slow skills ups<br>
red mobs - rare skill ups, of course very dependent on how often you actually hit mob<br>
<br>
As you can see, my research based on the tinkering method shows blue and light blue mobs are best for skill ups.<br>
<br>
Note: if your skill is far behind, try light blue mobs first or low AC blue mobs<br>
<br>
Professor Lexxi Ledenyetz<br>
Ice Giant hit tester<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukisarintenamin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KisarinTenamin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/16/02 1:36:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1718.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Skills ups</span><hr size=1> on the soulbinder thing, I do remember seeing a MOTD that said that attacking the soulbinders was a bannable offense.<br>
<br>
Then fact that you have gotten away with it means nothing, only that you did not get caught and that the system is not designed to monitor your actions and automatically report you.<br>
<br>
Tenamin Kor 36singer <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umosushi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mosushi</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/16/02 4:12:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1718.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Need to post more data Lexxi</span><hr size=1> Skill up rate also depends on your current skill.  It slows way down at 180, for instance and 0-10 is similarly slow.  If your warrior wasn't testing the same skill-range (eg. tested reds trying to raise 2hb 0-10 and tested blue with dual 1hs) or was using weapons with significantly different delays, it's not surprising he got different results.  <br>
<br>
After leveling many different characters up, I've found deep reds are by far the best for raising up neglected skills.  This is also why druid-PL'd characters typically have all melee skills max'd out.  If you're just max'ing out each skill every level, there's no point in wasting time on non-xp skill-up sessions.  Normal fighting can keep all your skills honed if you swap weaons appropriately.<br>
<br>
Also, I just petitioned attacking the soulbinder (gotta love 2-minute GM response on Stormhammer <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).  I talked to GM Phylum.  He's a real GM, not a guide.  His advice was not to attack them, but also said that it's not instantly a warning nor is it bannable.  He said that the activity is frowned upon because in rare situations, you might move the soulbinder from his position.  If he moves, he won't bind people anymore.  If he stops binding people, that falls under &quot;disrupting game-play for others&quot;.  He said that some GM's might in rare situations issue a warning for this.  He didn't mention banning, but I'd imagine if you found a way to move the binder around and kept doing it after being warned that you might end up banned.<br>
<br>
Basically, if you don't move him, you're fine.  If you do move him, you better have a caster with you to play soulbinder for anyone that needs a bind until you can shift the binder back into place.  Considering the time I've spent hitting him, I'd say it's nigh impossible to move him.  Up to you whether you attack him or not, but this chat put a green light on attacking the soulbinders for me.  It's not an everyday thing -- perfectly acceptable risk for a couple hours a month at most. <p>Mosushi, Lizard Master of the Fish<br>
